":"circa 1456","Abt 1470":"circa 1470","1512":"1512","1534":"1534","1435":"1435","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1463":"1463","1485":"1485","1529":"1529","1537":"1537","Europe":"Europa","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bramford, Suffolk, England":"Bramford, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1440–June 1491":"1440–June 1491","1440–1491":"1440–1491","1435–1534":"1435–1534","1460–1560":"1460–1560","1462–1529":"1462–1529","1463–1512":"1463–1512","1477–Male":"1477–Deceased","1485–1537":"1485–1537","1420–1470":"1420–1470","–Female":"Deceased","before 1440":"before 1440","1440":"1440","1462":"1462","1560":"1560","1460":"1460","June 1491":"June 1491","1470":"1470","1491":"1491","abt 1456":"about 1456","Abt 1470":"about 1470","1512":"1512","1534":"1534","1435":"1435","1477":"1477","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1463":"1463","1485":"1485","1529":"1529","1537":"1537","Europe":"Europe","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Bramford, Suffolk, England":"Bramford, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Vassey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Vassy inCalvados, France."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Cynthia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek <i>Kynthia</i>, an epithet applied to the goddess Artemis, who was supposed to have been born on Mount <i>Kynthos</i> on the island of Delos. The mountain name is of pre-Greek origin. <i>Cynthia</i> was later used by the Roman poet Propertius as the name of the woman to whom he addressed his love poetry. The English given name was not used in the Middle Ages, but dates from the classical revival of the 17th and 18th centuries."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Narcisus","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Narkissos</i>. In classical mythology, Narcissus was a beautiful youth who fell in love with his own reflection in a pool of water and remained there transfixed until he faded away and turned into a flower. The legend purports to account for the name of the flower, a kind of lily, known in Greek as <i>narkissos</i>. The name is almost certainly of pre-Greek origin, but attempts have been made to link it with Greek <i>narkē</i> ‘numbness’. The vocabulary word in English and horticultural Latin denotes the genus of flowers that includes the daffodil. The name was common among slaves and freedmen in the early Christian era, and a Roman citizen bearing this name is mentioned in  St Paul's  Epistle to the Romans (16:11). One  St Narcissus  was bishop of Jerusalem in  195 ; another was a Spanish bishop put to death at Gerona under Diocletian in  <i>c.</i>307 ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":15,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Cynthia Narcisus Vassey was born in 1440, in Bramford, Suffolk, England as the daughter of Thomas S. Vassey and wife Thomas S. Vassey. She married John McKinley Collins about 1456, in Bramford, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in June 1491, in her hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1440–June 1491":"1440–juuni 1491","1440–1491":"1440–1491","1435–1534":"1435–1534","1460–1560":"1460–1560","1462–1529":"1462–1529","1463–1512":"1463–1512"